},"explanation":"The FTC's Click-to-Cancel rule and ROSCA both require that cancellation be at least as easy as signup; phone-only cancellation for online-signed subscriptions is non-compliant.","id":"ADDENDA-019-s1-0","recommendation":"Add: 'You may cancel your subscription using the same method you used to subscribe (e.g., online via your account).'","rule_id":"ADDENDA-019","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"addenda-ftc-click-to-cancel-rule","license":"Public domain or regulator re-use","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-12T00:00:00Z","source":"FTC Click-to-Cancel Rule","source_url":"https://www.ftc.gov/legal-library/browse/rules/negative-option-rule"}],"title":"FTC Click-to-Cancel alignment missing"},{"description":"modified Terms take effect by providing written notice to Provider, and Provider shall provide a pro-rata refund of any pre-paid fees covering the period after the effective termination date. Continued use of the Service after the effective date of any modification constitutes acceptance","document_position":2518,"excerpt":{"end_offset":2806,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":2518,"text":"e the subscription before the modified Terms take effect by providing written notice to Provider, and Provider shall provide a pro-rata refund of any pre-paid fees covering the period after the effective termination date. Continued use of the Service after the effective date of any modification constitutes acceptance of the modified Terms."},"explanation":"A clause that deems continued use of the service to be acceptance of unilateral amendments has been criticized as illusory: the party 'consenting' has no real notice and no real ability to refuse without disrupting their business. FTC guidance and courts increasingly require affirmative consent for material contract changes.","id":"DARK-009-s1-2518","recommendation":"Require affirmative consent (signed amendment or click-through) for material changes. Continued-use-as-acceptance is acceptable only for non-substantive changes after meaningful written notice and an opt-out window.","rule_id":"DARK-009","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-ftc-deception-statement","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"FTC Policy Statement on Deception (1983)","source_url":"https://www.ftc.gov/legal-library/browse/ftc-policy-statement-deception"}],"title":"Continued-use-as-acceptance amendment clause"},{"description":"Indemnification language is present (`indemnification obligations`) but no clause caps the aggregate exposure.","document_position":6274,"excerpt":{"end_offset":6301,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":6274,"text":"indemnification obligations"},"explanation":"An indemnity carved out of (or simply not subject to) the liability cap can be the largest single financial risk a contract carries. A third-party IP infringement claim, a data-breach notification cost, or a regulatory fine can dwarf the contract value many times over. Confirm the carve-out is deliberate and proportionate to the indemnifying party's solvency.","id":"RISK-015-s1-6274","recommendation":"Either subject indemnification to a per-claim and aggregate cap, or confirm the carve-out is a deliberate trade for higher pricing / different insurance.","rule_id":"RISK-015","rule_version":"1.2.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Indemnification without aggregate cap"},{"description":"Used but not defined: Order Form.","document_position":1394,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1404,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1394,"text":"Order Form"},"explanation":"Title-Case phrases in a contract usually signal a defined term. When they aren't defined, readers must guess at the intended meaning. Either define them or use lowercase if the term is intended in its ordinary sense.","id":"STRUCT-006-s1-1394","recommendation":"Add a definition for each genuinely defined term, or change the casing if the phrase is being used in its ordinary sense.","rule_id":"STRUCT-006","rule_version":"1.1.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[],"title":"Undefined Title-Case terms: 1"},{"description":"The contract contains automatic-renewal language.","document_position":1507,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1517,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":1507,"text":"3. Auto-Renewal and Opt-Out. Each subscription term will automatically renew for successive terms of equal length unless Customer provides written notice of non-renewal at least thirty (30) days before t"},"explanation":"Auto-renewal commits the customer to another term unless they actively opt out. The notice window is the critical detail; verify it is reasonable and well-located.","id":"TEMP-004-s1-1507","rule_id":"TEMP-004","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"warning","source_citations":[{"id":"stat-16-cfr-425","license":"Public domain (US government work)","license_url":"https://www.usa.gov/government-works","retrieved_at":"2026-05-11T00:00:00Z","source":"16 C.F.R. Part 425 (FTC Negative Option Rule)","source_url":"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-16/chapter-I/subchapter-D/part-425"}],"title":"Auto-renewal clause present"},{"description":"The contract references data but does not separately allocate data ownership.","document_position":3002,"excerpt":{"end_offset":3015,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":3002,"text":"5. Data Ownership. Customer retains all right, title, and interest in and to the data, content, and information that Customer uploads to or processes through the Service (\"Customer Data\"). Provider acquires no ownership interest in Customer"},"explanation":"IP and data ownership are different. For SaaS, the customer typically owns its data; the vendor typically owns usage analytics. Address each explicitly.","id":"IPDATA-004-s1-3002","rule_id":"IPDATA-004","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Data ownership not separately addressed"},{"description":"Customer shall use the Service only for lawful business purposes and shall not: (a) use the Service to transmit spam, ma | Provider shall make the Customer Data available for export during this thirty (30)-day window and shall not delete or re","document_position":633,"excerpt":{"end_offset":1013,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":633,"text":"Customer shall use the Service only for lawful business purposes and shall not: (a) use the Service to transmit spam, malware, or unlawful content; (b) attempt to gain unauthorized access to the Service or Provider's systems; (c) use the Service to violate the rights of any third party; or (d) resell or sublicense access to the Service without Provider's prior written consent."},"explanation":"Negative covenants restrict what a party may do. Surfacing them collectively makes it easier to check they are intended and consistent with the overall deal.","id":"OBLI-005-s1-633","rule_id":"OBLI-005","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Negative covenants: 2"},{"description":"Provisions are stated to survive termination.","document_position":6134,"excerpt":{"end_offset":6167,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":6134,"text":"11. Survival. The following provisions survive expiration or termination of these Terms for any reason: payment obligations (Section 9), intellectual property rights (Section 5), indemnification obligations, confidentiality obligations, lim"},"explanation":"A survival clause names the obligations that outlast termination — typically confidentiality, indemnity, payment obligations accrued before termination, and choice of law.","id":"TEMP-006-s1-6134","rule_id":"TEMP-006","rule_version":"1.0.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Survival clause present"},{"description":"Survival clause does not appear to include: governing law.","document_position":6134,"excerpt":{"end_offset":6167,"section_id":"s1","start_offset":6134,"text":"11. Survival. The following provisions survive expiration or termination of these Terms for any reason: payment obligations (Section 9), intellectual property rights (Section 5), indemnification obligations, confidentiality obligations, lim"},"explanation":"Typical surviving obligations include confidentiality, indemnity, accrued payment obligations, and governing law. Missing any of these is common and worth confirming.","id":"TEMP-007-s1-6134","rule_id":"TEMP-007","rule_version":"1.2.0","severity":"info","source_citations":[],"title":"Survival list may be missing categories: governing law"}],"playbook_id":"saas-tos","playbook_match_confidence":1,"playbook_match_reasoning":"forced via sidecar to saas-tos","result_hash":"d046bb78130551c0dd2a69b1d4e8d16b012af9e5290f13583489178805bef40d","source_file":{"name":"saas-tos-minimal-pass.txt","sha256":"3f2fdd42031a1ef34c8248f1913e6986e79bdfa9fdd8e208ee902a0d73e4e8fa","size_bytes":1},"version":"9.41.0"}